{{use mdy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox book | name = The New York Apartment Houses of Rosario Candela and James Carpenter | author = Andrew Alpern | illustrator = | image = The New York Apartment Houses of Rosario Candela and James Carpenter.jpg | caption = Cover of hardcover edition | published = February 2, 2002 | subject = Architecture, history | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = Acanthus Press | country = United States | language = English | media_type = Print | isbn = 978-0926494206 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = 46385874 | pages = 350 pp. | website = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The New York Apartment Houses of Rosario Candela and James Carpenter''''' is an illustrated book by American architecture historian Andrew Alpern. The book was initially published on February 2, 2002 by Acanthus Press.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Linda|title=Currents: Architecture; An Inside Look At Grand Apartments|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/11/garden/currents-architecture-an-inside-look-at-grand-apartments.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 11, 2015|date=October 11, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Horsley, Carter H.|title=The New York Apartment Houses of Rosario Candela and James Carpenter|url=http://www.thecityreview.com/carpcand.html|newspaper=The City Review|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> The book discusses the works of prominent New York architects of the 1920s and 1930s, [[Rosario Candela]] and [[James Edwin Ruthven Carpenter, Jr.|J. E. R. Carpenter]], who helped shape whole blocks in Manhattan. Their buildings are now the standard residentials of the New York's elite.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Higging|first1=Michelle|title=Park Avenue Penthouse in a Rosario Candela Building|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/04/realestate/park-avenue-penthouse-in-a-rosario-candela-building.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 14, 2015|date=January 2, 2015}}</ref> The book contains a large number of photos and original floorplans of the discussed buildings, and several essays.
==See also== *''[[Art Deco Architecture: Design, Decoration and Detail from the Twenties and Thirties]]''
