{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Rembrandt-Lapidation-Saint-Étienne-MBA-Lyon.jpg | title=The Stoning of Saint Stephen | artist=[[Rembrandt]] | year=1625 | medium=Oil on oak panel | height_metric=89 | width_metric=123 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=Lyon | museum=[[Musée des Beaux-Arts de Lyon]] }}
'''''The Stoning of Saint Stephen''''' is the first signed painting by Dutch artist [[Rembrandt]], painted in 1625 at the age of 19.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rembrandt |first=Emmanuel |last=Starcky |publisher=Hazan |year=1990 |page=45 |isbn=2-85025-212-3}}</ref> It is currently kept in the [[Musée des Beaux-Arts de Lyon]].
[[File:Rembrandt's Stoning of Saint Stephen (detail).jpg|thumb|left|There are at least three self-portraits found in the painting.]] This work is inspired by the martyrdom of [[Saint Stephen]] which is recounted in [[Acts of the Apostles|Acts]] 7. This young deacon in the Christian community of Jerusalem was sentenced to death by stoning. The painting was influenced by the art of [[Caravaggio]] and [[Adam Elsheimer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Rembrandt ou la lumière réinventée |author=Françoise Caillet-Mangin |date=28 March 2006 |url=http://www.convivialiteenflandre.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=167 |publisher=Convivialité en Flandre |language=French |accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> It represents the moment when Stephen was stoned outside the city by his many tormentors (about twenty characters), and he utters his last words to Christ as the light around him shows that the heavens are open.<ref name="MBA">{{cite web |title=Harmensz van Rijn Rembrandt (Leyde, 1606 - Amsterdam, 1669), ''La Lapidation de Saint Etienne'' |url=http://www.mba-lyon.fr/mba/sections/fr/collections-musee/peintures/oeuvres-peintures/xviie_siecle/la_lapidation_de_sai?from_url=http%3A//www.mba-lyon.fr/mba/sections/fr/collections-musee/peintures/departement4598&b_start:int=22&startingReq=/sections/fr/collections-musee/peintures/oeuvres-peintures/#res_recherche |publisher=Musée des Beaux-Arts de Lyon |language=French |accessdate=19 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722174748/http://www.mba-lyon.fr/mba/sections/fr/collections-musee/peintures/oeuvres-peintures/xviie_siecle/la_lapidation_de_sai?from_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.mba-lyon.fr%2Fmba%2Fsections%2Ffr%2Fcollections-musee%2Fpeintures%2Fdepartement4598&b_start%3Aint=22&startingReq=%2Fsections%2Ffr%2Fcollections-musee%2Fpeintures%2Foeuvres-peintures%2F#res_recherche |archivedate=22 July 2011 |df= }} </ref>
The painting is divided into two distinct zones with a diagonal creating an effect of [[chiaroscuro]]: on the left, a man on horseback is in the shadow, and on the right, Stephen and his persecutors are in the light. Saul of Tarsus can be seen seated in the background holding in his lap the coats of the stoners. Some inaccuracies in the drawing can be seen.<ref name="MBA"/> The character behind Stephen seems to be a self-portrait done into a wider composition, as Spanish painter [[Diego Velázquez]] did in ''[[Las Meninas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rembrandt : 400 ans et toujours jeune ! |author=Karel Vereycken |date=13 December 2006 |url=http://www.solidariteetprogres.org/article2547.html |publisher=Solidarité et Progrès |language=French |accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref> John Durham suggests that Rembrandt "presents himself as a somewhat alarmed presence, a participant who may be having second thoughts about what was taking place."<ref>{{Cite book |last=Durham |first=John I. |authorlink= |title=Biblical Rembrandt: Human Painter In A Landscape Of Faith |publisher=[[Mercer University Press]] |year=2004 |location=Macon |page=60 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o1V_saJPmlUC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |id= |isbn=0865548862}}</ref>
